    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1925-04-22T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1925-04-22T23:00:00-05:00" n="684"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d684">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A 4 e/210: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-04-23T12:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 23, 1925—noon</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 23—7:26 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>167. Department’s 79, April 20, 3 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d684fn1">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Minister for Foreign Affairs states that according to present
                        calculations, and of course dependent upon French ratification of customs
                            treaty<note n="39" xml:id="d684fn2">
                            <ref target="frus1922v01#pg_282">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 282</ref>.</note> which French
                        Minister forecasted to him should take place in about two weeks,<note n="40"
                            xml:id="d684fn3">Instruments of ratification of the nine-power treaty
                            relating to the revision of the Chinese customs tariff were deposited at
                            Washington Aug. 5, 1925.</note> he desires to call Special Conference
                        for September 1st at Peking. Minister for Foreign Affairs seemed in some
                        doubt whether it was for Chinese Government to call the conference.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>From second paragraph Department’s 69, April 6, 11 a.m.<note n="41"
                            xml:id="d684fn4">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_627">p. 627</ref>.</note>
                        and from Department’s 79, April 20, 3 p.m., I assume that the Department
                        does not find an obstacle to the convening of the Special Conference or
                        cause for embarrassment in that regard in the fact that the participating
                        powers have not recognized the Chinese Government <hi rend="italic">de
                            jure.</hi>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Special Conference not discussed at meeting of Heads of Legation of April
                        21st. See my 158, April 17, 6 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d684fn5">Not
                            printed.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
